{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638032"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17687"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17687"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72037"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10448"},{"type":"tags","id":"10461"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24342"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72037"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring a spinning carnival ride, a person experiences a strong sensation of movement. When the ride suddenly stops, they feel as though they are spinning in the opposite direction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism responsible for this sensation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Otoliths become displaced from their normal position","Neural adaptation of vestibular neurons","Hair cells become temporarily desensitised","Blood pressure changes in the inner ear","Endolymph continues moving after head rotation stops"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen a person spins, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eendolymph fluid continues moving after head rotation stops\u003C/strong\u003E due to inertia. This ongoing fluid movement stimulates the hair cells in the semicircular canals, creating a false sensation of rotation in the opposite direction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtoliths become displaced from their normal position\u003C/strong\u003E - The otoliths are responsible for detecting linear acceleration and head position relative to gravity, not rotational movement.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural adaptation of vestibular neurons\u003C/strong\u003E - While neural adaptation occurs during prolonged rotation, the post-rotation sensation is primarily due to fluid mechanics rather than neural changes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHair cells become temporarily desensitised\u003C/strong\u003E - Although hair cells can exhibit adaptation, the primary mechanism causing this sensation is the continued movement of endolymph fluid.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood pressure changes in the inner ear\u003C/strong\u003E - Changes in blood pressure within the inner ear do not contribute significantly to vestibular sensations of rotation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis phenomenon demonstrates how the vestibular system relies on fluid dynamics to detect angular acceleration. The same principle explains why rapid head movements can cause dizziness in vestibular disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The semicircular canals contain endolymph fluid that moves in response to head rotation, stimulating hair cells.","Angular acceleration causes endolymph movement in the opposite direction to head movement due to inertia.","When rotation stops, endolymph continues moving briefly due to momentum, creating a sensation of movement in the opposite direction."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17687"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:23:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72037"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null